<P><TT><B><A NAME="17">17</A></B></TT>     All data are adjusted using the
Bureau  of Labor Statistics CPIUX1. It should be noted that the Senate Finance
Committee Advisory  Commission To Study the Consumer Price Index has determined
that the CPI overestimates the  increase in the cost of living from 0.7 to 2.0 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  percentage points. This in turn
has misled Members of Congress and President Clinton  into thinking that GDP,
productivity, and real  wages have grown more slowly than they really  have.
Indeed, without the upward bias in the CPI, real wages would have grown
significantly  since 1983 instead of stagnating.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="18">18</A></B></TT>     Average annual pay is published
by  the Bureau of Labor Statistics. These data are a broader measure of &quot;pay&quot;
than hourly wages  and cover 96.4 percent of wage and salary civilian
employment, compared with 68 percent for  average hourly wage data. Average
annual pay includes bonuses, tips, and some employer  contributions to deferred
compensation plans such as 401(k) plans.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="19">19</A></B></TT>     The growth in median family
income  follows a similar pattern. From 1979 to 1994, median family income
adjusted for  inflation decreased 1.1 percent. It declined by 7.4  percent from
1979 to 1982, then increased 12.6 percent from 1982 to 1989, then declined  5.2
percent from 1989 to 1994.
</P>
<P><TT><B><A NAME="20">20</A></B></TT>     Hourly wage data are available
only  for private nonfarm production and nonsupervisory employees.
