<head>
<title>Respeced Conservatives</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<H2>Gingrich, Armey Lead Poll of Respected Conservatives
</H2>
<H3>Leadership Institute donors respect the Speaker and House Majority Leader for Strong Leadership in Congress</H3>
<P></center>
<BR>
<BR>
	<DD>Rejecting media attacks on the current Congress, Leadership Institute donors selected Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich and House Majority Leader Dick Armey as the conservatives leaders they respect most.<P>
<I>	Speaker Gingrich received nearly 40% of   the vote.  U.S. Rep. Armey got nearly 30%</I>.<P>
 <DD>	The mail-in survey was conducted in June.  It suggested no names.  In all, 722 of those who sent in the survey volunteered which leader or leaders they respect.
<DD>	According to Morton Blackwell, president of the Leadership Institute, the <a href="respect.html"> Results</a> indicate the conservative grassroots favor leaders who take bold and principled stands for concerns  of both economic and social conservatives.
<DD>	"The natural governing majority in America is a coalition of economic and social conservatives," Morton said.  "The survey results reflect that."  
<BR><DD>	U.S. Rep. John Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee, won 79 votes, tying for fifth place with radio talk-show host Rush Limbaugh.
<BR>	<DD>In third, with 89 votes each, were conservative thinkers Jack Kemp and William Bennett.
<BR>	<DD>GOP presidential candidates rounded out the top 10.  Bob Dole received 72 votes-22.6 percent of the total vote for Republican presidential candidates.  Pat Buchanan received 63 votes and U.S. Senator Phil Gramm got 55.
<BR> <DD>	None of the respondents selected President Bill Clinton as the most-respected conservative leader.
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER><I>If you missed the Leadership Institute supporter survey but still wish to complete it, please contact Ric Andersen at (800) 827-5323 or (703)247-2000.</I></CENTER>
<P>
<BR>
