<hr size=3 width=50%>
<p>
<b>Crime and Law: Criminal Law and Procedure 
</b>
</center>
<ul><p>
<b>Books:</b>
<p>
<a href="/heritage/congress/chapt4.html">What the 104th Congress Did to Combat Crime</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/moffit.htm">Robert E. Moffit</a>. (<i>Reviewing the Revolution: Conservative Successes in the 104th Congress</i>)<br>

<a href="/heritage/issues96/chpt8.html">Crime</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/fagan.htm">Patrick F. Fagan</a> and <a href="/heritage/staff/moffit.htm">Robert E. Moffit</a>.  (<i>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</i>)
<p>
<b>Policy Papers:</b>
<p>
<li>10/28/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bg1097.html">How State and Local Officials Can Combat Violent Juvenile Crime</a>  by James Wootton and Robert O. Heck. (State Backgrounder #1097/S)
<li>10/15/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/lect573.html">Cutting Crime and Restoring Order: What America Can Learn from New York's Finest</a> by William J. Bratton. (Lecture #573)
<li>9/1/96 <a href="/heritage/p_review/sept96/cal.html">Out of Order</a> By Steven G. Calabresi. (September-October 1996, Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship)
<li>8/21/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bg1089b.html">Getting Backup: Twenty-One Steps Public Officials Can Take To Support Their Local Police</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/moffit.htm">Robert E. Moffit</a> and <a href="/heritage/staff/meese.htm">Edwin Meese III</a>. (Backgrounder No. 1089)
<li>8/19/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/fyi117.html">What the 104th Congress Did to Combat Crime</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/moffit.htm">Robert E. Moffit</a>. (F.Y.I. #117)


<li>8/6/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bg1089.html">Getting Backup: Twenty-One Steps Public Officials Can Take To Support Their Local Police</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/moffit.htm">Robert E. Moffit</a> and <a href="/heritage/staff/meese.htm">Edwin Meese III</a>. (State Backgrounder No. 1089) 
<li>7/12/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bgup279.html">The Clinton Administration's Continuing Retreat in the War on Drugs</a> by John P. Walters and James F.X. O'Gara. (Backgrounder Update No. 279)
 <li>1/1/96 <a href = "/heritage/p_review/jan96/meese.html">How Washington Subverts Your Local Sheriff</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/meese.htm">Edwin Meese III</a> & Rhett DeHart.  (January-February 1996 Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship)
<li>7/1/95 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/prabra.html">Litigation Tariff: The Federalist Case for National Tort Reform</a> by Spencer Abraham (Summer 1995 Policy Review).
<li>4/1/95 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/pr1allen.html">The Courage of Our Convictions: The Abolition of Parole Will Save Lives and Money</a> by George Allen. (Spring 1995 Policy Review)
<li>10/11/94 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/fyi40.html">Reining in Federal Judges: The Crime Bill's Unexpected Gift to the States</a> by Wesley Smith and <a href="/heritage/staff/seay.htm">Douglas Seay</a>. (F.Y.I. No. 40)
<li>9/10/91 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/lect342.html">The Quest for Justice: Natural Rights and the Future of Public Interest Law</a> by William H. Mellor III and Clint Bolick. (Heritage Lecture No. 342)

</ul>
